00:00:00.240 --> 00:00:13.140
Good day, I'm Norman Wildberger. Last time&nbsp;
we introduced poly numbers, which are simpler&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:13.140 --> 00:00:20.580
versions of polynomials. Today we're going to&nbsp;
talk about elementary arithmetic with these new&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:20.580 --> 00:00:28.230
objects. So I remind you of the basic setup: we&nbsp;
have the positive numbers 0, 1, 2, 3, and so on.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:29.460 --> 00:00:38.430
We said last time that a positive poly number&nbsp;
is an object created from a list of positive&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:38.430 --> 00:00:46.380
numbers written vertically with a bracket on top.&nbsp;
That defines a new type of mathematical object,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:46.380 --> 00:00:55.560
poly num plus. So it's like a positive number but&nbsp;
a positive poly number. I should say, perhaps,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:55.560 --> 00:01:00.900
that this list is by definition non-empty, so&nbsp;
it must have at least one entry in the list.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:02.550 --> 00:01:10.500
We'll say that if we order the elements p0, p1&nbsp;
down to pk, then this is the zeroth coefficient,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:10.500 --> 00:01:17.850
this is the first coefficient, and so on. P sub i&nbsp;
is the i-th coefficient of P, and we're starting&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:17.850 --> 00:01:25.950
our indexing at 0 up at the top. In a little bit&nbsp;
of abbreviated notation, instead of writing this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:25.950 --> 00:01:33.570
big list like this, we'll just write P equals&nbsp;
P sub i. We'll say that the degree of our poly&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:33.570 --> 00:01:42.840
number is the largest index K which has a non-zero&nbsp;
coefficient. So we read down to the last fellow&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:42.840 --> 00:01:53.070
which is non-zero, and the degree is the index.&nbsp;
The zero polynomial right, so we will not talk&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:53.070 --> 00:01:59.430
about the degree of the zero polynomial. I&nbsp;
remind you of our convention for equality:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:59.970 --> 00:02:06.000
if you have a poly number, you're allowed to add&nbsp;
zeroes at the bottom of it, and we say it has not&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:06.000 --> 00:02:11.850
changed to add zeros or, if necessary, subtract&nbsp;
zeros. We can say that another way by saying that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:11.850 --> 00:02:18.210
P sub i can be considered to be zero if the&nbsp;
index r happens to be bigger than the degree.

00:02:20.490 --> 00:02:25.920
Here's a definition of addition of two&nbsp;
polynomials: so here's one poly number P,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:25.920 --> 00:02:33.810
and here's another poly number Q. The coefficients&nbsp;
are P sub i here and Q sub i. Then we say that the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:33.810 --> 00:02:42.810
sum is the poly number R whose i-th coefficient&nbsp;
is just the sum of the i-th coefficients of P and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:42.810 --> 00:02:51.870
Q. For example, to add this poly number to this&nbsp;
one, we add the zeroth coefficients, we add the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:51.870 --> 00:02:58.560
1 coefficients, the 2 coefficients, and the 3&nbsp;
coefficients. The 3 coefficient here is zero,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:58.560 --> 00:03:06.840
so we're adding zero to this 7. Another example,&nbsp;
even simpler: the poly number 11 plus the poly&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:06.840 --> 00:03:13.710
number 7 equals the poly number 18. So we see that&nbsp;
ordinary addition of numbers is kind of contained&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:13.710 --> 00:03:19.770
in this arithmetic of poly numbers, just by&nbsp;
looking at very simple ones of degree zero.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:19.770 --> 00:03:26.520
And then it's not too hard to see that addition&nbsp;
satisfies the commutative law, and it satisfies&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:26.520 --> 00:03:33.840
the associative law, and that if you add the zero&nbsp;
polynomial to any poly number P, you get back P.

00:03:33.840 --> 00:03:41.640
Addition is easy; multiplication is a little&nbsp;
bit less easy. Okay, so here's the definition&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:41.640 --> 00:03:47.250
of multiplication of two polynomials, which I hope&nbsp;
you figured out from the examples I gave you last&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:47.250 --> 00:03:54.870
time. So here's one poly number P and another&nbsp;
poly number Q. Then their product, P times Q,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:54.870 --> 00:04:02.730
is the new poly number R whose i-th coefficient is&nbsp;
given by this expression. Let's have a close look&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:02.730 --> 00:04:11.520
at it, it's very important. It's the sum over&nbsp;
all positive numbers k and l that add up to i,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:11.520 --> 00:04:22.170
the sum over all those k's, P sub k times Q sub l.&nbsp;
So we're multiplying one coefficient from P times&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:22.170 --> 00:04:29.450
one coefficient from Q, and we have to choose the&nbsp;
indices so that they add up to our given index i,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:29.450 --> 00:04:38.210
and we add up all those possible products&nbsp;
over all such possible indices. So here's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:38.210 --> 00:04:44.840
a very simple example: three times two equals&nbsp;
six. So here the zeroth coefficient times the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:44.840 --> 00:04:51.800
zeroth coefficient here is the zeroth coefficient&nbsp;
here. Let's have a look over here: poly number 4,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:51.800 --> 00:05:00.650
1 times the poly number 3, 7. To find the zero&nbsp;
coefficient of the result, we look at the zeroth&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:00.650 --> 00:05:06.230
coefficient here times the zeroth coefficient here&nbsp;
because zero plus zero is the only way of getting&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:06.230 --> 00:05:12.950
two numbers adding up to zero. We get 12. When we&nbsp;
look at the first coefficient, so this would be i&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:12.950 --> 00:05:21.170
equals 1, then we have to look at all pairs of the&nbsp;
indices that add up to 1. So we could take 0, 1;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:21.170 --> 00:05:30.440
they add up to 1, or 1, 0. And the corresponding&nbsp;
products are 4 times 7 plus 1 times 3. We add them&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:30.440 --> 00:05:39.860
together, we get 28 plus 3 is 31. How about&nbsp;
when i is equal to 2? What coefficients add&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:39.860 --> 00:05:44.420
up to 2? What about 1 plus 1? That equals 2.&nbsp;
Okay, so we have to take that product 1 times&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:44.420 --> 00:05:53.090
7. So here's a little bit more complicated: 1,&nbsp;
1, 0, 2 times 3, 1. For the zeroth coefficient,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:53.090 --> 00:05:58.280
it's the product of these two. The first&nbsp;
coefficient is this times this plus this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:58.280 --> 00:06:05.390
times this. This coefficient is this times this&nbsp;
plus this times this plus this times this. The&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:05.390 --> 00:06:12.260
two coefficients that add up have to add up to&nbsp;
2. And this one here, that's when i equals 3,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:12.260 --> 00:06:18.710
we can get that by taking this times this, which&nbsp;
is 0 here, plus this times this, that's also 0,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:18.710 --> 00:06:25.220
plus 2 times 1, that's 2, plus 0, so we get a&nbsp;
2. But we also get a coefficient from i equals 4&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:25.220 --> 00:06:33.410
because that's the result when k is 2 and l equals&nbsp;
2. This times this equals 8. That's multiplication&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:33.410 --> 00:06:42.770
of two polynomials, and it satisfies some various&nbsp;
laws: the commutative law, the associative law,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:42.770 --> 00:06:49.940
a distributive law with respect to addition. And&nbsp;
note that I'm using the usual convention that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:49.940 --> 00:06:55.940
multiplication takes priority over addition, so&nbsp;
you have to multiply these two first, you multiply&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:55.940 --> 00:07:04.820
these two, and then you add these two resulting.&nbsp;
And also P times the poly number 1 is just P.

00:07:04.820 --> 00:07:09.590
So in fact, you are very familiar with this kind&nbsp;
of multiplication but in a slightly different&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:09.590 --> 00:07:14.960
form. Let's illustrate that by looking at this&nbsp;
particular example. So convince yourself that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:14.960 --> 00:07:23.750
the poly number 3, 1 times the poly number 2,&nbsp;
3 is 6, 11, 3. 2 times 3 is 6, 9 plus 2 is 11,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:23.750 --> 00:07:32.900
and 0 plus 3 plus 0 is 3. Now that computation&nbsp;
is reflected in the ordinary way in which we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:32.900 --> 00:07:42.770
multiply the Hindu-Arabic numbers 13 times&nbsp;
32. 13, 32. Because one way, a very naive way,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:42.770 --> 00:07:48.560
of thinking about how this product works is to&nbsp;
take, well, this is 2 times 3, which is 6, that's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:48.560 --> 00:07:55.160
the ones result. How many tens do we get when we&nbsp;
multiply? Well, there's 2 times this 10, that's 2&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:55.160 --> 00:08:00.800
tens there, and there's also 3 times this 3 tens,&nbsp;
which is another nine tens, so altogether there&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:00.800 --> 00:08:08.540
are 11 tens that result. And how many hundreds are&nbsp;
there? Well, we get hundreds by taking this 10 and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:08.540 --> 00:08:17.780
multiplying it by these three tens, 1 times 3 is 3&nbsp;
hundreds. So the product of these two numbers is 6&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:17.780 --> 00:08:26.450
ones, 11 tens, and 3 hundreds. Now, we know that&nbsp;
we don't usually leave it in this form because we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:26.450 --> 00:08:34.610
don't like to have numbers bigger than nine in any&nbsp;
one spot, so we would convert this 11 tens into&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:34.610 --> 00:08:43.010
1 hundred and 10 tens, giving us altogether&nbsp;
416. But if we left it at this stage here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:43.010 --> 00:08:48.080
then we would have exactly what we got when&nbsp;
we multiply the corresponding polynomial.

00:08:48.080 --> 00:08:56.600
Multiplication is really not much different from&nbsp;
the way you multiply two numbers ordinarily in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:56.600 --> 00:09:03.080
the Hindu-Arabic system. And of course, this&nbsp;
multiplication reflects the usual multiplication&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:03.080 --> 00:09:11.480
of two polynomials. If we take the polynomial&nbsp;
3 plus x and the polynomial 2 plus 3x, now we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:11.480 --> 00:09:18.770
multiply them together using the distributive&nbsp;
law. We get 6, the number of x's is 2 plus 9,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:18.770 --> 00:09:27.680
that's 11, and the number of x squared is 1 times&nbsp;
3, which is 3. So that's the point of it all. We&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:27.680 --> 00:09:33.590
are mimicking what happens with polynomials but&nbsp;
we're doing so in a way that does not involve x's.

00:09:33.590 --> 00:09:38.090
Next time, we're going to look at&nbsp;
arithmetic with poly numbers in even&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:38.090 --> 00:09:43.400
more detail. I hope you'll join me for that.&nbsp;
I'm Norman Wildberger. Thanks for listening.

